<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-390-304  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 390 304.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telecommunications  June 1989 v23 n6 p37(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The changing role of satellite in telecommunications: satellitesystem alternatives can provide service comparable to or betterthan cable systems. (report by COMSAT's World Systems Div) (PublicNetworks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Crockett, Bruce.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Communications Satellite Corp's (COMSAT's) World Systems Divcommissioned a study to determine the role of satellites in futureinternational communications.andP;  One conclusion seems clear:International Message Telephone Service (IMTS), which isessentially voice, will shift to non-IMTS traffic, driven byworldwide demand for data, facsimile and video services.andP;  Fivesatellite systems are examined and each is described ascost-competitive with fiber cable in the Atlantic Ocean Region(even more so in the Pacific because distances are greater).andP;  Thestudy reveals that both satellites and fiber optics have a role toplay: satellites are suited to broadband, high-speed datatransmissions, and they are especially cost-efficient onlong-haul, thin routes; fiber-optic cable is effective onhigh-traffic, point-to-point routes, especially for interactiveapplications, which require low propagation delay.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Communications Satellite Corp. World Systems Div. (reports).andO;Topic:     Satellite CommunicationsFuture TechnologiesSpecialized Common CarriersFiber opticsTelecommunicationsDigital communicationsTelephone systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechartgraph.andO;Caption:   Performance and cost characteristics of the five satelliteconcepts. (table)The advantages of satellites. (chart)IMTS and non-IMTS services. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>